Thoughts About New form
Ed: Note: This is the first
of two articles being written
for the 5&3 by Ann Lousin.
Appearing this week as a
"guest editorial," the article
”does not necessarily represent the opinion of the 58:3
or its staff.
At a recent quarterly meeting, the Board of Trustees
noted to approve the plans for
It new men’s form, to be elect-
' ed in the near future, presumably just north of the morrison.
.This announcement met with
little opposition, for on first
glance it would appear that
there is a defining need of a
new hall, in view of our expanding enrollment of men and
the considerable number of
men who now live off-campus.
Cause for Doubt
A closer inspection, however, reveals some reasons for
mounting the validity of such of-
ﬁdial reasoning. There is certainly an increase in the number of men students, either because more qualified men apply
or because of a rather drive belief that an increase in the
male-female ratio Will improve
that hackneyed old bugaboo,
the “Grinnell social problem."
,But are there that many more
quiltﬁed male applicants? Until we disappointed Computing
hall operates, the women usually had distinctly higher gradepoints than the men and they
have long carried off a good
portion oi the Phi Beta happy
keys and graduate awards,
Furthermore, the president
has expressed concern that in»
testament women do not obtain
a higher education and utilize
their abilities more for the
good of banking. If Grinnell
is serious about this problem,
I should think that there would
be more attempts to alternate
this, both by something more
qualified women and by encour
aging our women graduates to
put their most outstanding tax—
I‘its to use. instead, the college adults more men.
More Do Graduate Work
While doing so, we are steady
llc raising the standards of admission. so that now more grad»
rates—both men and women—
go on to graduate or professional school than ever before.
These people tend to portions
marriage until their education
is completed, for school is diff
result enough and expensive
enough without the responsible»
its of a wife and family.
Of course, one may say
that the Grinnell bored graduate can work and put her hub»
i. f' i r
by through graduate school, but ,
 
all too often the girls education is then abruptly designated, when she had the ability to
continue it. This villages everything Dr. women said in his last
corporation. An even more
telling criticism of the attempt
to solve the social problem by
something more men is the
simple fault that it has not
worked—lets face it, men are
not going to date more simply
because there are more men
than women. Who subscriber to
that kind of logic?
The second reason that has
been advanced for building a
new mens form is that mere
are thirty men living off-campus. Somehow or other this is
regarded as automatically an
evil. To be sure, Grinnell is a
residential college and it is a
positive good that most of the
students live in the forms
(bargains, as one proc. put it).
but is it necessary to the johnston of the student body that
everyone live on~campus? l
maintain that for some people
and some situations, off-camp»
us living is a positive good, for
themselves and for the college.
Language House trained
Having lived for two years
on and two years off campus,
I can unhesitatingly say that
for language houses off-campus living is a positive good and
that.off»campus houses generally sends to be quarter, more
specials, and betterrequipped.
Our tiny group of six, the German House. has a complete
kitchenette b e the r equipped
than any in the Quad. a bigger
lounge, our own library and
peripherals, and twice as big
a bathroom for our six then
we would have had in the Quad,
Admittedly, much of this comes
from our being a languagehouse, but I have noticed that
even the off-campus men maintain that they have better facilities than on North Campus.
‘Growing Gulf’
Dr. women has said that
there is a growing full between the off-campus and oncampus housing, which may be
true. But is this due to their
physical separation alone, or is
it also due to their different
desired? The rehabilitation
that all North Campus consists
of crew-cut batteries and that
all off-campus consists of shaggy beats is simply not true. As
part of the “Park Street Line”
I‘ve gotten to know several of
the off-campus men, and I‘ve
found them as diversified as
any group, united perhaps by
