graduation Class Bequeatlis Heritage
0! Challenging Attitude Toward Rules
To the Editor-x
Although it is too early in the
year to become continental
about the inevitably emotional
visual of graduation, it is not
too early to take notice of what
the passing of the class of 1964
will mean for this institution.
With mixed emotions we are
now processing the withdrawal
from student government of the
spokesman of the class of '64
and their replacement by a
new class which promises to
be different.
The alumni, I am told, are
more various to see this class
leave and would move heaven
and earth to see that nothing
like us happens to this school
again. What sort of people were
we that we have earned such
ill favor? The class of 1899 left
us the Women’s Gym; What, if
anything,’ is the heritage of the
class of 1964?
First, I believe it is proper
to speak of the class as an
identifiable entity, because,
though this year’s student government was only representing
student opinion as a whole,
much or the time, they were by
far the most articulate and consistent forces for rules reforms
in the recent history of the job
legs.
As a group the class, and
particularly its leadership, can
be describe we were vocal.
we were pop cal and (somewhat less) legalistic, we were
idealistic, we held very liberal
moral beliefs and we were self<
centered. Does this constitute a
heritage?
Apparently it does Students
in American colleges have al«
ways shared at restrictions on
their freedom of action, but the
traditional response has been a
blend of sponsored department
and covers disobedience. Students have not admitted that
college rules actually had the
typically binding character of
a fundamental moral law; violation of such rules was only
a crime When you were caught.
The contribution of the class
of '64 was a new, “experimental" attitude regarding rules
which was at once moralistic,
idealistic, and responsible and
a new connection of student as
a political instrument of reform.
Peter and Jack told us that a
rule was a thing we ought to
obey, and if opening it proved
various the only responsible resource would be to write a new
rule.
The alternative for continuing to big the question with institutionalized hypocrisy (by
an intentionally inefficient rules
enforcement system) hardly
'seemed attractive The student
body responded, to the agreement of many, by election the
most articulate portion of
1964's “beatles horse" to the
highest office: in student government.
What then is the legacy of
these people? Despite the anonymous criticism of the sherman
regime by those seeking his office, every platform contains
the plants of rules reform and
moral commitment to rules.
What is new, we see, is the
“attitude" which our new
leaders will manifest while code
 
finding the work of the old
guard, The new leaders will
wear skills and more acceptable haircuts, but they understand their offices in those
same terms which their predecessors calculated,
There is one change in emphasis, however, which seems
both totally and regrettable.
The plans of responsibility met
with student opposition while
the plans of reform met with
administrative opposition. Of
the two, the administration
(along with those mysterious
does, the alumni) proved the
more resistant. What we now
see is a new student commit»
ment to the old, conscious
rules.
To make matters worse, our
efforts at publication our cause
have put the administration
and their policies very much on
the spot, with the effect that
they now respond from experience and from an understandable reaction to outside pressure,
College students of the late
1950's are already called the
“synthetic" or “silent” generation. If we were self-centered
and dramatically disinterested,
we were certainly not silent on
the issue of personal freedom
The leadership of this class,
moreover, was concern in its
conviction that it’s beliefs were
totally accessible; it labeled
to develop a concrete “student
ethic" to justify its moral
france. This ethic, instead as
any single ethic existed,
claimed that all decisions of
mobility were “up to the individual" unless they affected
someone else's rights. The most
sophisticated statement’of this
philosophy is found in the engagement Report, specifically
in the report from the committee on “student responsibility."
The best employment of the
philosophy in 3 rules system is
found in the same report under
the Committee on rules.
The strain Of idealism has
succumbed wholly to arbitration. The recent tutorials open
rooms path was signed by
many who saw nothing Wrong
with taking “any" approach to
the administration, "so long as
it works," The idealogical assault did not get results; it is
hardly likely that an opportunity which packs Conviction will
succeed.
’ Cynicism‘and disinterest are
the dominant goods of the std»
sent body now, The political experiment clearly puzzles. Yet applying student leaders, despite
disappointment with the sherman administration’s liability
to produce the sought reforms,
are unable to reject the political approach to the rules problem, '
So Where do we stand with
respect to last year? Relations
with faculty, trustees, administration and alumni are considerable incorporated.‘Students
are enhancing rules they consider conscious. The political
approach to rules, having
failed, remains the dominant
self-connection of student got—
