A review of the play. “The
ratings Brought to Mary,”
presented by the Grinnell College Players February 22 and
23.
By Sam Schuman
”The ratings Brought To
Mary" is a peculiar and difficult play It attempts to present a Christmas miracle,
without becoming a Christmas
miracle play, Claudel has
achieved this purpose largely
through characterization. He
has made Violaine, the central
character of the play, a painted
human being, but not a saint.
para, Who should be the evil
sister is, in her way, available,
and, in the final scenes of the
work, catholic, Thus Claudel
has decided simplemindedness
and created a complex and
worthwhile piece of drama,
But this factor of literary
subtlety becomes a matter of
great electrical difficulty.
Gretchen meyer as Violaina
was forced to attempt to pro<
sent a character whom the
audience could accept as both
a human being and a miracle
worker, Miss meyer successfully created this demanding
part. This success was due in
large part to the poverty and
simplified in both her speech
and movement,
The role of para, played by
Sue congo, also seemed quite
well done Despite her entrance
as the wicked witch of the
West (an entrance detailed
by the play), Miss month gave
us a para who was, in her own
words “a naked sword," which
is a far cry from the bloody
are which might have been
forced upon us by a lesser ac»
press.
Keith hilton, as values the
knife~throwing farmer, played
quite well Claudel’s character
whose feet are planned so firmly in the soil that he is confused by anything more spiritual than crop rotation
The fact that no one left the
theatre during the long and did.
ficult dialogue is sufficient
praise for Ken Freedman’s pre
selection of Pierre de Craonr
Terry McCoy as the father
was particularly outstanding in
Act 1, scene 1.
Although the technical as<
posts of the show, designed by
Mr. William M,,Sherman of
wellington, were superb, we
are rather happened and
assumed to think that Grinnell
must have outside support, both
intellectual and financial, to de«
gently stage a show which was
otherwise competent, exciting,
and worthwhile.
