T. persons Labels 20th Century as Turbulent, Creative;
Sees Societal qualification; cards generation in Studies
Dr. elliott persons, professor
of sociology at Harvard, was a
ampus guest
army this week
as part of the
' “Interdisciplin-
are Seminar on
rder.” A for-
her student at
- School of ecoomics and the
U diversity of
Heidelburg, he
' has h e a d e d
”R50” H a r card’s Interdisciplinary Department of
Social Relations for the past 20
years.
By Karen robinson
“I believe that the twentieth
century will come to be viewed
like the investments century —
a turbulent time, uncomfortable to live in, but highly creative,” assisted elliott persons, noted sociologist.
“gui- generation has been
through tremendous s o c i a 1
changes. Nineteen courtesy
was the end of the Old Europe,
The precariously b a la n c e d
state system of the 19th century
was ended. The determination
of extra-European territories
was gone permanently. Inter»
nav transformation took place.
The next generation has a terrible job ahead of it, but there
is some prospect of a stability»
tion with the more Violent dis
instances near the periphery
rather than in the center. This
does mean a confirmation of
corps in Latin America and
situations like South V i e t
Nam," he concluded.
persons denied that modern
society is sending toward more
rehabilitation and rapidly or»
derek society “except in per;
gods of crisis and only in limited sectors."
He used the modern university as an example, “The ma-
 
dean university is an extraord
entry phenomenon. Never has
mere been an organization so
complex which has allowed for
so much autonomy."
persons was a biology major
as an undergraduate at Am»
first. He has studied at the
London School of Economics
and Heidelberg University as
well as at Harvard
"1 cannon voice any degrees
at being a generation. Specialization in generation, or method
in madness," he said carefully,
“is actually a better expression
because there must be some
organizing principle which links
g e n e r a 1 studies. Being a
specialist is safer; a generation
runs the risk of superficiality;
but if knowledge, which is systematic, is to be organized,
generations are necessary."
persons noted another modern intellectual d i l e m m a,
“There is a deep tension in intellectual circles today between
the organized skepticism of
science and the need for the
kind of Commitments which
can be the basis for action and
yet be intellectually responsible. The extremists forest intellectual responsibility in order to push their cause, but for
me majority this deep tension
is not so easily resolved,”
