element. The armor of reform
and idealism has been replaced
by cynicism and district. Undeniably, this is a “revoltin'
predictions.”
Without taking the time to
defend this stand, I suggest
ah immediate change of direction. The optimum solution of
good rules and strict enforcement is intolerable. Since poor
rules are the "given" or unchangeable factor, it seems that
the only realistic response is
the traditional one of discrete
version of the rules governing
personal conduct.
That is to say, I advocate a
return to hypocrisy. It is no
more unprincipled to disregard
a rule affecting personal moral
conduct which you sincerely impose for moral reasons that it
is to subject yourself to an unrealistic, artificial and angeles<
family restriction code of conduct. The rapidly understood
flexibility of rules which has
generally presented in our universities and colleges seems to
me far more compatible with
the serious business of an edt‘
nation than the foolishly right
conduct control, with its accompanying department, n n d e r
which we are now living.
