Cartoonist Coplivoies Audience —
Draws. Talks. Jokes at Lecture
By Pam Clay
r “My normal working day
starts at the office at 9:00—
just in time to take a coffee
break at Bishops," said Frank
Miller, cartoonist for The Des
points Register and Tribune.
“1 try to return to the office
in Lime to leave for lunch; then
I go back and draw for about
two hours!" Mr. Miller said
that this ”daily schedule" does
point up one important thing
about editorial cartoonists, “To
{have an idea one must have
anything to say; 90% of the
work and time is getting ideas."
Mr. Miller was graduated
from the University of Kansas
with a degree in fine arts. He
went on to study at the Ram
ins City Art institute. He came
to Des points about ten years
ago after working on the can<
ﬂas City Star.
To prove that his artistic parents have never been ignored,
Mr. Miller explained how he
listed everything possible our-
g his five year saint with
Uncle Sam. What artistic are<
union it took to council names
on thousands of sellers, to
council stripes, oak leaves, and
stars for the officers; the air
force (unofficially) even expanded pin-up girls on the
notes of their planets ”The
armed forces have this necessity called a katrina, and every
time we moved I painted a sign
“LATRINE CLOSED OUTi"
.Why, my art work is in Germany, France, Korea . . .1”
Mr. Miller used visual aids
to the best advantage throughout his lecture. The first cartoon he drew showed the typical image of a cartoonist: beast, long hair, sunglasses, and
manuals. He has received various comments about his career
such as: “You don’t look like
one,” ”You actually make a
living doing that?” and, “Why
 
don’t you say something fun»
ny?"
He demonstrated some typical commercial cartoons and
then gave his own version— entirely different but much more
truthfull Mr. Miller said his
cartoons are drawn “the way
I see life"
“The editorial cartoonist gets
lots of help from world leaders." he said. To illustrate his
point he mentioned Castro’s
board and boots, and Johnson‘s
ranch and hat.
The beginning of a cartoon of
Khrushchev was blessed by
sophomore Phil Bernstein. He
got to keep the original but perhaps blessed a little too soon;
all he got was one line indicating a bald crown.
Mr. Miller said that he and
other cartoonists have been attacked by members of the John
march society because “humor
is a luxury we cannon afford in
th e s e terrible times.” He
claimed that Americans have
always had humor and that it
is now a necessity. Paul severe
and Benjamin Franklin were
the first American editorial cartoonists. but even the cave
drawings. which record how
people lived, are editorial car<
tools, he pointed out.
Mr. Miller’s technique is the
old-mentioned one of pen and ink
9“ smooth paper; he is not technically correct but feels free to
dream up his own images of a
automotive, character, or setting. ”We must think, read, listen. and then speak and act,’
he said. ”Everyone must do
this, not only the cartoonists
and reporters. In Russia the
press is a tool of propaganda—
it can happen here.”
Reading from former frequent Kennedy’s tribute to Rob»
art Frost, Mr. Miller quoted,
". . . art established the basic
human trucks. . ."
”Drawing cartoons is a job
I love; I can’t think of anything I would rather do."
 
